The Paperboys concert was amazing.  I have seen them twice before in Leavenworth and I have all of their albums.  The talent of the band is unbelievable.  However, I was very disappointed with the sound system. For one thing, it was just way too loud for the size of the venue.  I was in the sixth row and my friends and I felt like we were being blasted with sound.  Even more frustrating was that the mix for the vocals seemed way off. We could hardly hear what Tom was singing. It sounded like he was under 10 feet of water. It probably sounded ok in the balcony but it was very muddy in the front rows.  The sad thing is that the acoustics are very good in the theatre.  I sing with the Choral Society and we have sung there several times. There is no need to blast the music like they are in a stadium.  Anyway, we still enjoyed the show, but were disappointed with the sound system. Please bring them back and turn down the amps! :) Thanks!

column17: Excellent!  Thoroughly enjoyed the performance and was glad to see an audience of all ages!  (I appreciated the opportunity to meet Michael after the performance - he's charming!)

Mike Wylie was very engaging. His genuine joy in interacting with the audience was unsurpassed. Regardless of the small audience size, he entertained, engaged, and performed with the greatest interests. Sound was an issue for both the announcer and actor as was conversation during the performance. It sounded like one of the entry doors was left open and what was meant to be a private conversation was now public. A friend had heard about his performance from a grade school grandchild who was impressed with his message and performance. The children, whom he selected to interact on stage were delighted to be chosen. His Q & A after was engaging and encouraged those free thinking artisans in the audience to continue to see this gift as valuable, as he relayed his interest in people watching and mimicing voices/body language as a child, which led to his performance career.  We are glad to hear that he will be returning next year.

The PHT staff also did a fantastic job of carrying on without grumbling or apologizing what was out of their control. Really, a fun evening.

Was a little disappointed the feature comedienne (Kira Soltanovich) didn't attend; although, it's understandable the weather can't be controlled by humans--and therefore, her plane was grounded in Seattle.  Despite the missing headliner, kudos to the staff and anyone else's contribution in successfully arranging a "replacement" show.

column18:
I would like to see more movies at Gesa.  It’s a good venue for “arty” or even foreign films.  However, those films require a first class marketing program which I don’t think Gesa has yet managed to accomplish.  Looking at the list of where we might hear of these films, there doesn’t seem to be any outlet targeting college students at Whitman or Whitman’s arts/drama/music departments.  There are documentaries  (such as “giants Rising”) that would be of interest to younger people if the marketing informs them effectively and in advance.  At the screening, there were movies previewed that I was unaware of (not in the Gesa brochure that was handed out).  There has been Quest classes on movies but I don’t think those potential audiences have been targeted.  
I would also be interested in seeing Gesa explore subscribing to NTLive programming.  That might be a partnership with the colleges/university offering a student discount price.  Please look into NTLive (National Theater of London productions that are filmed on the final night of performances that are at times better than the actual show — I saw a live performance and later the NTLive film of the live production: the camera angles gave much better reading of the actors than seeing it live.). I highly recommend nearly all of their productions.

column17: very good

Loved this film--and the title was on point:  Holy Frit! indeed.  It encompassed captivating images; sound was just right; value was increased by the education which I feel I received watching the process of how to create stained/fused glass.  Such a journey for the artist, the production crews--glass makers, installers and camera manipulators, plus the courage it took to take on such an enormous endeavor.  The gigantic risks taken and the expenses incurred--constantly having to evolve was a great lesson for us all.
column18: This was one of the most memorable films I've seen at the Powerhouse.  Full of fun, humor, challenge, beauty, collaboration, glass artistry and more--with the ultimate result.  This film hooked me on researching the largest commissioned stained-glass project in the world (at the time) because it made me want to know more.  What an incredible feat to have considered, accepted and produced.  When I saw the eyes of Jesus (I'm not particularly religious.), it touched me in a deeply spiritual way from an artistic perspective.

It became more than the sum of dark and light or the holocaust and survivorship--developing into an all-encompassing life and love of mankind thereafter.  That we’re all present in this “middle” of our lives because we’re not at the hour of our birth and not yet dead, was very powerful and thought-provoking.

It was so random to have a horror film in the middle of the rest of the films which were mostly light hearted. The event was good, I enjoyed it. However, with the short film "Three Doors Down", the horror about a murderous elf, that film should have been last and a warning about viewer discretion should have been advised. A lot of people left during this film and I think a warning would have been appropriate as all the rest of the films were so lighthearted in comparison. Giving the viewer time to get out of the theater before being subjected to watching... whatever I had watched, would have been appropriate. It was dark, profane, disturbing and utterly unsuitable. One clip could only be called a horror short, I don’t care that they tried to be humorous with spurting green blood instead of red. column18:
I have noticed this at many concerts, not just the Birbiglia show.  
If there is one thing that could take the Powerhouse from good to great, it would be to allow seating of patrons one hour before show time. After a certain age, adults do not enjoy being mashed together like a techno club mosh pit or a cattle truck.  If lighting and sound checks need to be done before the show, I would humbly suggest that the technicians come in a half hour earlier.  If the performer gets too claustrophobic waiting an hour before the show, then we might consider updating the Green Room.
I have observed patrons becoming angry,  waiting  half an hour for the  doors to open. lve also observed the opposite.  The inevitable outcome of opening the house only 30 min before show time, is that you've trained patrons to arrive at the last minute and then they are being seated after the show  has begun.  This is incredibly distracting for the audience and  perhaps for the performer as  well.

I realize there are several things that need to take place (will call, ticket scanning, coat check, bar, etc.) in a relatively small space, but the crowding means people have to wait outside for a while so that they can squeeze between people to get through the lobby. Perhaps longer hours for the bar, moving will call, or something like that would be helpful for reducing congestion. That said, the staff were all very friendly, welcoming, and helpful!

Loved the feel but was unimpressed with the house lights turning on just for the performers to "see our response." As a viewer I was taken out of the experience more than two times due to the house lights being on. Reference the russia tour of Billy Joel when he explains how much of an AV fail that is. When the house lights go down...keep em down. If the artist requests to have the audience a bit visible for the use of a practical part of the show that is planned, suggest other lighting sources from the stage such as the warmer lights used half way between the first act, to reflect on the audience. This venue is small enough to not have to worry about a disconnect from the performer to the audince, so I will stand by the fact that the house lights should stay down unless it is an emergency or intermission...or over lol.

I thought the show would be focused on escapes, which I really don’t enjoy (also, I thought the photo gave kind of a dark impression of both him and the show—not appealing to me). I bought the tickets later not realizing this was the same show I’d read about earlier, and regretted it. But we went anyway, so as not to waste the money spent, and happily it was more focused on other kinds of magic than on escapes, so we enjoyed it.
